  "text": "Upon induction of negative selection, cellular adhesion is regulated in a complex manner. Discoidin domain receptor 1 (ddr1), a collagen-binding receptor gene, and ®bulin 2, a gene encoding an extracellular matrix protein with epidermal growth factor-like domains, are down-regulated, suggesting a reduced capacity of thymocytes to attach to the extracellular matrix. In contrast, cell±cell adhesion is enhanced. The integrin ligand intercellular adhesion molecule (icam)-1 and bystin-like (bysl), the mouse homologue of a human cytoplasmic component of a cell adhesion complex, are up-regulated. Furthermore, the proline±serine±threonine phosphatase-interacting protein 1 (pstpip1), also known as cd2bp1, is downregulated, leading to enhanced CD2-mediated adhesion [CITATION_1] . Thus, apoptotic thymocytes apparently loosen their binding to the extracellular matrix while tightening their interactions with neighboring cells. The shift in adhesion may allow more ef®cient engulfment by phagocytic cells within the thymus. Cytoskeletal genes, which may be involved in adhesion processes, are regulated in a similar complex manner as adhesion-mediating genes (Fig. 3) .",
